83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
House Bill 4079
Sponsored by Representative MCDONALD, Senator NERON MISSLIN, Representatives ANDERSEN, CHOTZEN,
FRAGALA, RUIZ, Senator FREDERICK; Representatives EVANS, GAMBA, GRAYBER, HUDSON, JAVADI,
MUNOZ, NELSON, NGUYEN D, NOSSE, PHAM H, SOSA, WALTERS, WISE, Senators GELSER BLOUIN,
GOLDEN, PHAM K, REYNOLDS (Presession filed.)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure as introduced. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability
standards.
Digest: Tells public schools to have a policy for how to respond to immigration issues at the
school. (Flesch Readability Score: 65.1).
Directs school district boards and governing bodies of institutions of higher education to adopt
policies that address how the school district or the institution of higher education will respond when
a federal immigration authority enters school property or a campus. Prescribes the requirements of
the policies.
Declares an emergency, effective on passage.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to policies for when federal immigration authorities enter public education property; cre-
3 ating new provisions; amending ORS 339.405; and declaring an emergency.
4 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
5 SECTION 1. (1) As used in this section:
6 (a) “Federal immigration authority” has the meaning given that term in ORS 180.805.
7 (b) “School district” includes an education service district and a public charter school.
8 (c) “School district board” includes the board of directors of an education service district
9 and the governing body of a public charter school.
10 (d) “School property” means any real property owned, controlled or used by or on behalf
11 of a school district that is accessed by students of the school district on a regular basis.
12 (2) Each school district board shall adopt a policy that addresses how the school district
13 will respond when a federal immigration authority enters school property.
14 (3) The policy adopted under this section must:
15 (a) Identify at least one administrator for each school district, and at least one designee
16 of the administrator, who shall be designated to respond when a federal immigration au-
17 thority enters school property. The response must include:
18 (A) Recording the time and location of the presence;
19 (B) Consulting with legal counsel, when feasible;
20 (C) Verifying the credentials and purpose of the federal immigration authority, including
21 determining if access is sought under a judicial warrant or court order; and
22 (D) Responding to any judicial warrant or court order.
23 (b) Require that, unless otherwise prohibited by law, reasonable efforts are made to
24 provide notice as expediently as possible to a student or to the parent or guardian of a stu-
25 dent when the school district has provided information related to the student to a federal
26 immigration authority.
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 74

HB 4079
1 (c) Require that notice that a federal immigration authority is present on school property
2 is provided to:
3 (A) Students and the parents or guardians of students attending the school where the
4 federal immigration authority is on school property; and
5 (B) The community of the school where the federal immigration authority is on school
6 property.
7 (d) Specify the contents and delivery requirements of the notice required under para-
8 graph (c) of this subsection, including the requirements that the notice:
9 (A) Must include at least the following information:
10 (i) The general location of the federal immigration authority; and
11 (ii) Whether classes or school operations are affected by the presence of the federal im-
12 migration authority.
13 (B) May not disclose any of the following information:
14 (i) Personally identifiable information; or
15 (ii) Other information that may not be legally disclosed.
16 (C) May not disclose information when the disclosure:
17 (i) May threaten the health or safety of the students or employees of the school district;
18 or
19 (ii) Is prohibited by a court order.
20 (D) Must be provided as expediently as possible by existing methods used for providing
21 electronic communications to students, parents and guardians or to the school community.
22 (e) Ensure compliance with ORS 180.805 and 181A.826.
23 (f) Require the provision of written guidance in relation to federal immigration authority
24 efforts, including clarifying:
25 (A) The difference between court orders and administrative orders;
26 (B) Which areas of the school are public or private and under which circumstances pri-
27 vate areas may be accessed by a federal immigration authority; and
28 (C) Which actions may constitute interference with a court order or lawful access to
29 public areas.
30 (g) Require that annual training is provided to the employees of the school district on:
31 (A) The expectations of the employees in relation to federal immigration authority efforts
32 on school property; and
33 (B) The guidance described in paragraph (f) of this subsection.
34 (h) Require that the policy adopted under this section and the guidance described in
35 paragraph (f) of this subsection be made available:
36 (A) In the student handbook; and
37 (B) On the school district’s website in culturally appropriate languages that are used to
38 communicate effectively with parents and guardians of students of the school district.
39 (4) The Department of Education shall submit an annual report on the provisions of this
40 section, including the number of notifications issued under subsection (3)(c) of this section
41 during the year, to an interim committee of the Legislative Assembly related to education.
42 (5) The State Board of Education shall adopt model policies and may adopt rules under
43 this section. When adopting model policies, the board shall consult with the Attorney Gen-
44 eral to ensure consistency with model policies adopted as provided by ORS 180.810.
45 SECTION 2. ORS 339.405 is amended to read:
[2]

HB 4079
1 339.405. (1) As used in this section:
2 (a) “Evacuate” means a procedure used when students and staff need to move from one location
3 to another.
4 (b) “Hold” means a procedure used to keep students and staff in classrooms while a disruption
5 or minor emergency is resolved.
6 (c) “Lockdown” means a procedure used when a threat or hazard is inside the building.
7 (d) “Secure” means a procedure used when a threat or hazard is outside the building.
8 (e) “Shelter in place” is a procedure used to respond to and take protective actions based on a
9 threat or hazard that may include an earthquake, tsunami or other natural or environmental hazard.
10 (2) Each school district must maintain a comprehensive safety program for all students and staff.
11 The program must include procedures for:
12 (a) Responding to emergency situations that address an immediate threat to safety, including an
13 evacuation, a hold, a lockdown, a secure and a shelter in place;
14 (b) Providing communicable disease management;
15 (c) Responding to medical emergencies; [and]
16 (d) Providing instruction as described in ORS 339.408[.]; and
17 (e) Responding to a federal immigration authority on school property as described in
18 section 1 of this 2026 Act.
19 (3) The State Board of Education may adopt rules related to a program required under this
20 section.
21 SECTION 3. (1) Section 1 of this 2026 Act and the amendments to ORS 339.405 by section
22 2 of this 2026 Act become operative July 1, 2026.
23 (2) Section 1 of this 2026 Act and the amendments to ORS 339.405 by section 2 of this 2026
24 Act first apply to the 2026-2027 school year.
25 (3) Notwithstanding the operative date set forth in subsection (1) of this section, school
26 districts may revise a comprehensive safety program before the operative date set forth in
27 subsection (1) of this section to include provisions related to responses to a federal immi-
28 gration authority on school property.
29 SECTION 4. (1) As used in this section:
30 (a) “Campus” means any real property owned, controlled or used by or on behalf of an
31 institution of higher education that is accessed by students of the institution of higher edu-
32 cation on a regular basis.
33 (b) “Federal immigration authority” has the meaning given that term in ORS 180.805.
34 (c) “Governing board” means:
35 (A) The governing board of a public university listed in ORS 352.002.
36 (B) The board of education of a community college district.
37 (C) The Oregon Health and Science University Board of Directors.
38 (d) “Institution of higher education” means a public university listed in ORS 352.002, a
39 community college operated under ORS chapter 341 or the Oregon Health and Science Uni-
40 versity.
41 (2) Each governing board shall adopt a policy that addresses how the institution of higher
42 education will respond when a federal immigration authority enters a campus.
43 (3) The policy adopted under this section must:
44 (a) Identify at least one administrator for the institution of higher education, and at least
45 one designee of the administrator, who shall be designated to respond when a federal immi-
